---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { breadcrumbSchema } from '../data/seo';

const title = 'About The Reflex Hub - Fast, Free Skill Tests';
const description =
  'Learn what The Reflex Hub is, how our free reaction, typing, and clicking tests work, and why your scores stay private in your own web browser.';
const path = '/about';

const schema = [
  breadcrumbSchema([
    { name: 'Home', path: '/' },
    { name: 'About', path },
  ]),
];
---

<BaseLayout title={title} description={description} path={path} schema={schema}>
  <div class="mx-auto max-w-6xl px-4 pt-10">
    <h1 class="font-display text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight sm:text-4xl">About The Reflex Hub</h1>

    <article class="copy mt-6">
      <p>
        The Reflex Hub is a collection of free browser games that measure human performance skills: reaction time,
        clicking speed, typing speed, aim precision, and short term memory. Every test runs entirely in your browser,
        gives you a score in seconds, and shows you how that score compares with published averages. The site exists
        for gamers warming up before a match, typists checking their words per minute, students taking a study break,
        and anyone who simply wants to know how quick they really are.
      </p>

      <h2>Our Philosophy</h2>
      <p>
        We built this site around a few stubborn principles. First, instant loading: every page is static, lightweight,
        and playable within about a second, even on a mid range phone. Second, no signup: you will never hit a login
        wall, an email capture form, or a locked result. Third, no dark patterns: there are no fake leaderboards, no
        countdown timers pressuring you to share, and no results held hostage behind a paywall. And fourth, your data
        stays yours. Scores and personal bests are stored with localStorage, a standard browser feature that keeps data
        on your own device. Nothing you do here is uploaded to a server or connected to your identity. The tradeoff is
        that scores do not sync between devices, and we think that is a fair price for genuine privacy.
      </p>

      <h2>How We Benchmark Scores</h2>
      <p>
        A score only means something next to a reference point, so every test on The Reflex Hub compares your result
        against widely published averages rather than numbers we invented. For reaction speed, we use the commonly
        cited average visual reaction time of 273 ms. For typing, the reference is the average typing speed of 40 WPM,
        with professional typists landing around 65 to 75 WPM. For clicking, the benchmark is roughly 6.5 clicks per
        second on a standard 10 second test. Percentile tables on each results card are calibrated to these figures, so
        when the site says you beat 80 percent of people, that claim is anchored to real published data.
      </p>

      <h2>Honest Limitations</h2>
      <p>
        Browser tests are accurate enough for meaningful self comparison, but they are not laboratory instruments, and
        we would rather say so plainly. Your measured reaction time includes hardware and software latency: monitor
        refresh rate, mouse and keyboard delay, and browser overhead can add anywhere from 10 to 50 ms to the number
        you see. A 60 Hz display alone can add up to 16 ms compared with a 240 Hz gaming monitor. That overhead is
        roughly constant on a given setup, which means your scores are highly comparable with each other over time,
        just not perfectly comparable with a friend testing on different hardware. For honest progress tracking, use
        the same device and browser, and pay attention to trends rather than single runs.
      </p>

      <h2>Not a Medical Tool</h2>
      <p>
        The tests on this site are for fun, practice, and casual self measurement. They are not a medical or
        psychological diagnostic tool, and no score here can identify, rule out, or monitor any health condition. Many
        things move these numbers day to day, including sleep, caffeine, stress, and simple practice effects. If you
        have concerns about your reflexes, attention, coordination, or memory, please speak with a qualified healthcare
        professional rather than relying on a browser game.
      </p>

      <h2>Get in Touch</h2>
      <p>
        Found a bug, spotted an inaccurate benchmark, or have an idea for a test you would love to see? We read every
        message. Head over to the <a href="/contact">contact page</a> and tell us what is on your mind.
      </p>
    </article>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
